sols_latex:
The solution for a differential equation of the form
$\frac{\mathrm{d}x }{\mathrm{d} t} = Ax(t)$ and A is 2 by 2 and
diagonalizable has the form

$x(t) = c_1v_1e^{\lambda_1 t} + c_2v_2e^{\lambda_2 t}$ where $\lambda$
are the eigenvalues of A and $v$ are their respective eigenvectors.

$c_1, c_2$ can be obtained by plugging in the initial condition
$x(0) = \begin{bmatrix}
4\\1

\end{bmatrix}$

Solving $\begin{bmatrix}
4\\ 1

\end{bmatrix} = c_1\begin{bmatrix}
1\\2

\end{bmatrix}
+ c_2\begin{bmatrix}
0\\1

\end{bmatrix}$ should give you $c_1 = 4, c_2 = -7$

therefore the solution is $x(t) = 4e^{t}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\2
\end{bmatrix} - 7e^{0.5t}\begin{bmatrix}
0\\1
\end{bmatrix}$

